            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>Dukes&rsquo; flexibility will be important as he takes the field this fall. Although both Dukes and senior signal-caller Chris Dapolito will take snaps at quarterback, Roof named sophomore quarterback Mike Schneider the Blue Devils&rsquo; starter for what has been described as a more pass-oriented offense than Duke has run in years past.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s difficult because they throw multiple formations at you,&rdquo; Aguanno said. &ldquo;They&rsquo;ve got people running all over the place.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Yet the Blue Devil defense has been equal to the task of containing new offensive coordinator Marty Galbraith&rsquo;s complicated offense. Defensive end Phil Alexander enters his senior year 20 pounds stronger and, as Roof called it, &ldquo;stronger to the point of attack.&rdquo; Casey Camero has bulked up as well, checking in at 275 pounds and shifting to defensive tackle, according to fellow tackle Orrin Thompson.</p>
<p>In the linebacking corps, Aguanno appears to have picked up for the Blue Devils where Ryan Fowler left off, notching three tackles for loss in the first scrimmage.</p>
<p>&ldquo;We lost Ryan, but we feel like our linebacking corps hasn&rsquo;t lost a step,&rdquo; Aguanno said. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve got experience everywhere. As far as Malcolm [Ruff] goes, Malcolm&rsquo;s just been an absolute beast. He got really strong last off-season.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Despite their losses, then, the Blue Devils have remained upbeat, motivated and focused on the upcoming season.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s the culture that he&rsquo;s brought about,&rdquo; said senior cornerback Kenny Stanford. &ldquo;I think as long as Coach Roof is here, you&rsquo;ll see that excitement.&rdquo;</p>
<p><font color="#003399">ROSTER NOTES</font></p>

